{"summary":"Both amendments identify real lineage-correlation defects. The current legacy fallback silently conflates distinct attempts in cases where the store lacks a reliable stable identifier, which can rewrite or collapse retry history and undermine the milestone/task audit trail.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-12-5e41079a","decision":"accept","rationale":"`find_matching_running_task_run` and `record_task_run_start` do in fact treat any sole open legacy row (`run_id == None`) as reusable for a later named start, then backfill that row instead of appending a new attempt. That is fine for replaying the same in-flight run after a partial write, but it is not safe for a genuine later retry after upgrade: the older open row is mutated into the new named run and the earlier attempt disappears from lineage. Given the stated requirement to preserve retry/audit history by run, that silent merge is a correctness defect."},{"amendment_id":"fr-12-eaae97d7","decision":"accept","rationale":"`TaskRunEntry::same_attempt` falls back to `started_at` equality whenever either side lacks `run_id`, and `collapse_task_run_attempts` then merges entries on that basis, including terminal rows with the same outcome. There is no guarantee that `started_at` is unique for distinct legacy/no-`run_id` attempts, so reused or truncated timestamps can cause separate retries in the same `project_id` to collapse into one visible history entry. Because `run_id` is intentionally optional for backward compatibility, relying on timestamp uniqueness here is too weak and breaks retry visibility."}]}